ion easier.  The distribution is called Lycoris, and as much as I knew I would like Linux once I started using it this has blown me away!<br>
<br>
I downloaded the CD image (that took a while, but well worth it), burned it to a CD, and booted my laptop to the CD.  It took me through the install with a gui, very user friendly, and even had a solitaire game built in so you didn't get bored while it finished loading files. :P  It detected and installed ALL of my hardware (drivers all built into the OS), even my obscure proprietary laptop stuff that was a pain the arse to install and get working under windows, and automatically set it up so it was ready to go when I first logged into it.  I logged on and could immediately get on the internet and access the other computers on the network.  It has so much stuff built in that I had to install separately under win-blows.  ICQ, AIM, IRC, graphics editor (a good one, not like MS paint!), browser, ftp client, email client, office software (word processor/spreadsheet/financial manager/etc.), pretty backgrounds and screensavers, cd burner, games (including some neat old arcade games), realplayer, mp3 and mpeg player, adobe acrobat...all that stuff that would take me several hours to install under windows is already there.  It's also very easy to figure out if you know how to use windows...but everything is so much more customizable.  You don't have to use any consoles or text commands if you don't want to, you can do everything in the graphical user interface.  My linux friends tell me it is also much more stable than windows (it would kinda be hard not to be I'm thinking), but I have not used it long enough to find that out.  Are you sold yet? :P<br>
<br>
The only thing I'm disappointed about is that I was expecting it to run a lot faster than win98 (this is an amd k6-2 400 with 64mb ram though; nothing runs terribly fast).  I guess since I got the bulky, shiny, graphical, user-friendly version it's got all the extra stuff that slows windows down too though...it still runs a hell of a lot faster than win2k.<br>
<br>
SO, if you've been putting off installing linux on one or more of your systems because it would be too hard to figure out how to use a new OS or you'd have trouble finding software that works with it, don't wait anymore. :P  Lycoris IS EASIER to set up and use than windows, and is a lot less headache...it comes with built in software that does most everything you could want, and if you have windows programs that you just can't do without (like EQ :P) I understand you can still run them under linux with vmware or other programs that emulate the win32 kernel in linux.  Bobolink can tell you more about that though -- Bobo, is it possible to run EQ on a linux system with a windows emulator?  *thinks about deleting windows from all her systems and installing lycoris linux*  It also makes it very easy to have a dual-boot system if you want windows and linux on the same system.<br>
<br>
Oh and that brings me to another point, TRK has our very own Linux guru to bug with questions in case we have any. /duck Bobo :P<br>
<br>
